<node CREATED="1634920791693" ID="ID_1021171206" MODIFIED="1634927282455" TEXT="Types">
<richcontent TYPE="NOTE">&lt;html&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;
    
    
  &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;body&gt;
    &lt;p style=&quot;border-right-style: none; padding-bottom: 0px; margin-top: 0px; font-size: 1.6rem; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-style: none; padding-top: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; margin-bottom: 0; padding-right: 0px; font-family: -apple-system, system-ui, BlinkMacSystemFont, Segoe UI, Roboto, Source Sans Pro, Helvetica, Arial; color: rgb(55, 62, 63); vertical-align: baseline; margin-right: 0px; line-height: 1.5; border-left-style: none; margin-left: 0px; padding-left: 0px; border-top-style: none; border-top-width: 0px&quot; id=&quot;types-of-jenkins-popeline&quot; charset=&quot;utf-8&quot; class=&quot;ibpage-article&quot;&gt;
      &lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;&gt;Jenkins Pipelines can be either - a Declarative pipeline or a Scripted 
      Pipeline. Declarative pipeline makes use of numerous, generic, 
      predefined build steps/stages (i.e. code snippets) to build our job 
      according to our build/automation needs whereas, with Scripted 
      pipelines, the steps/stages can be custom-defined &amp;amp; used using a groovy 
      syntax which provides better control &amp;amp; fine-tuned execution levels.&lt;/font&gt;
    &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/article&gt;
    &lt;/section&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
      
    &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</richcontent>
