<node CREATED="1634927009327" ID="ID_736499929" MODIFIED="1634927133385" TEXT="Ping Thread">
<richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      <font color="rgb(55, 62, 63)" size="16px" face="-apple-system, system-ui, system-ui, Segoe UI, Roboto, Source Sans Pro, Helvetica, Arial">it sends a ping message that the receiving end will reply to. The ping thread measures the time it takes for the reply to arrive, and if it&#8217;s taking excessive time (currently 4 minutes and configurable), then it assumes that the connection was lost and initiates the formal close down. </font>
    </p>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <p style="border-right-style: none; padding-bottom: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-style: normal; margin-top: 0px; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; font-size: 16px; border-right-width: 0px; white-space: normal; border-bottom-style: none; padding-top: 0px; font-weight: 400; border-left-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; padding-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0; font-family: -apple-system, system-ui, system-ui, Segoe UI, Roboto, Source Sans Pro, Helvetica, Arial; color: rgb(55, 62, 63); vertical-align: baseline; margin-right: 0px; line-height: 1.5; border-left-style: none; margin-left: 0px; border-top-style: none; padding-left: 0px; text-transform: none; border-top-width: 0px; word-spacing: 0px; letter-spacing: 0.1px" charset="utf-8">
      This is to avoid an infinite hang, as some of the failure modes in the network cannot be detected otherwise. The timeout is also set to a long enough value so that a temporary surge in the load or a long garbage collection pause will not trip off the close-down.
    </p>
    <p style="border-right-style: none; padding-bottom: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-style: normal; margin-top: 0px; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; font-size: 16px; border-right-width: 0px; white-space: normal; border-bottom-style: none; padding-top: 0px; font-weight: 400; border-left-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; margin-bottom: 0; padding-right: 0px; font-family: -apple-system, system-ui, system-ui, Segoe UI, Roboto, Source Sans Pro, Helvetica, Arial; color: rgb(55, 62, 63); vertical-align: baseline; margin-right: 0px; line-height: 1.5; border-left-style: none; margin-left: 0px; border-top-style: none; padding-left: 0px; text-transform: none; border-top-width: 0px; word-spacing: 0px; letter-spacing: 0.1px">
      Ping thread is installed on both controller &amp; agent; each side pings the other and tries to detect the problem from their sides.
    </p>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <p>
      <font color="rgb(55, 62, 63)" size="16px" face="-apple-system, system-ui, system-ui, Segoe UI, Roboto, Source Sans Pro, Helvetica, Arial"><span style="background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-style: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; font-size: 16px; white-space: normal; font-weight: 400; font-family: -apple-system, system-ui, system-ui, Segoe UI, Roboto, Source Sans Pro, Helvetica, Arial; color: rgb(55, 62, 63); display: inline !important; text-transform: none; word-spacing: 0px; float: none; letter-spacing: 0.1px" charset="utf-8">The ping thread time out is reported through java.util.logging. Besides, the controller will also report this exception in the agent launch log. Note that some agent launchers, most notably SSH agents, writes all stdout/stderr outputs from the agent JVM into this same log file, so you need to be careful.</span></font>
    </p>
  </body>
</html></richcontent>
</node>
<node CREATED="1634927221348" ID="ID_941017993" MODIFIED="1634927278752" TEXT="How to Store Credentials">
<richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      <font face="-apple-system, system-ui, system-ui, Segoe UI, Roboto, Source Sans Pro, Helvetica, Arial" color="rgb(55, 62, 63)">Credentials can be stored securely in Jenkins using the Credentials plugin, which stores different types of credentials like - Username with a password, SSH username with the private key, AWS Credentials, Jenkins Build Token, Secret File/Text, X509 &amp; other certificates, Vault related credentials securely with proper encryption &amp; decryption as and when required.</font>
    </p>
  </body>
</html></richcontent>
